WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.620 --> 00:00:03.220
With life getting more demanding and hectic all the time,

2
00:00:03.380 --> 00:00:07.189
it seems there's only one way to cope: multitasking. Gurus

3
00:00:07.220 --> 00:00:09.160
and life hackers make a living telling us how to

4
00:00:09.180 --> 00:00:12.540
get better at it. But can we actually multitask? The

5
00:00:12.600 --> 00:00:15.200
term was first used in the '60s to describe computer

6
00:00:15.260 --> 00:00:18.500
performance. The human brain, though, is not a computer, and

7
00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:22.600
human attention is a very limited resource. Some psychologists model

8
00:00:22.610 --> 00:00:25.450
visual attention as being like a spotlight. It can only

9
00:00:25.460 --> 00:00:28.830
be shone in one direction at any one time. Our

10
00:00:28.840 --> 00:00:31.700
primary focus, what we're paying most attention to, is like

11
00:00:31.740 --> 00:00:33.940
the brightly lit area in the center of the beam.

12
00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:37.080
It can also be understood as being like a zoom

13
00:00:37.140 --> 00:00:40.220
lens. We can choose to narrow our focus to concentrate

14
00:00:40.260 --> 00:00:42.960
in detail or widen it to be aware of more

15
00:00:42.980 --> 00:00:46.200
things simultaneously, but we can't be zoomed in and out

16
00:00:46.240 --> 00:00:50.580
at the same time. Even though we're constantly receiving a

17
00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:54.260
huge amount of information from our senses, it's only possible

18
00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:56.360
for a small amount to make it through to conscious

19
00:00:56.440 --> 00:01:01.000
awareness. Watch the next section very carefully and pay particular

20
00:01:01.020 --> 00:01:03.800
attention to how many balls bounce in the circle.

21
00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:14.380
How many can you count? Seven, right? But did you

22
00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:18.620
also notice that little dinosaur? What about the changing shape

23
00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:21.600
of the circle or the smiley face on one of

24
00:01:21.660 --> 00:01:26.100
the balls? This shows just how powerful focused attention is.

25
00:01:26.460 --> 00:01:29.420
Being able to filter out irrelevant detail is an amazingly

26
00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:31.670
useful tool, but it means we can miss things that

27
00:01:31.680 --> 00:01:35.410
are right under our noses, an effect known as inattention

28
00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:38.880
blindness. You can see this very clearly in the famous

29
00:01:38.900 --> 00:01:43.310
invisible gorilla experiment. When asked to concentrate exclusively on how

30
00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:46.700
often basketball players in white pass the ball, most people

31
00:01:46.740 --> 00:01:50.010
completely miss the gorilla walking across the screen and beating

32
00:01:50.040 --> 00:01:54.080
his chest. We just don't have the capacity to process

33
00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:56.980
everything at once. This is a particular problem when we

34
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.420
try to multitask. We can switch attention from one task

35
00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:03.880
to another and back again, but when attention is overloaded,

36
00:02:04.200 --> 00:02:06.830
we miss things, and the result is nearly always that

37
00:02:06.860 --> 00:02:09.630
we perform tasks less well than we would doing them

38
00:02:09.660 --> 00:02:12.600
one at a time. It's only truly possible to do

39
00:02:12.660 --> 00:02:15.209
two things at once if they require different sets of

40
00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:18.920
cognitive resources. For example, it's totally possible to read a

41
00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:22.400
book and listen to music at the same time, which

42
00:02:22.420 --> 00:02:24.769
would suggest that driving while talking on the phone is

43
00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:27.400
not a problem as long as it's a hands-free phone.

44
00:02:28.180 --> 00:02:31.420
It's not that simple, though. Research has shown that while

45
00:02:31.480 --> 00:02:33.860
talking on the phone, we have a tendency to create

46
00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:37.720
mental images, and this uses the same visual resources needed

47
00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:41.590
for driving. And if visual resources become too stretched, it's

48
00:02:41.620 --> 00:02:44.080
perfectly possible for a driver to look directly at a

49
00:02:44.180 --> 00:02:47.820
hazard but, just like with that little dinosaur, fail to

50
00:02:47.860 --> 00:02:51.040
see it. Not everything will make it through to conscious

51
00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:55.470
awareness. So multitasking makes us at best inefficient and at

52
00:02:55.560 --> 00:02:59.060
worst downright dangerous. If you're feeling like you should be

53
00:02:59.100 --> 00:03:02.560
doing seventeen things at once, remember, that's just not the

54
00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:07.600
way your brain is wired. Thanks for

55
00:03:07.640 --> 00:03:10.600
watching. Don't forget to subscribe and click the bell to

56
00:03:10.640 --> 00:03:14.440
receive notifications for new videos. See you again soon.
